A bone house is still fascinating after 100 years. See Gaudi's interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs are like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are open fish mouths.
This is Casa Batlló, designed by the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
The house, with its organic forms, was nicknamed '& quot; Bonehead' by locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splinters and mosaics, the shed-like façades and the ubiquitous soft lines are typical features of Antonio Gaudi's Art Nouveau style.
The façade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures that remind of nature and living beings.
Only on closer inspection does one realize that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm, and elaborate order.
At night, the whole façade becomes even more vivid and dramatic, and the special illumination adds to the brightness of the colours.
The same sweeping lines and sinuous shapes dominate the interior of the house.
Waving wood copies the window frames, railings, door decorations, even peepholes and moldings.
The Batlló house, in the Eixample district, on the lively Passeig de Grácia Nr. 43, was created by the conversion of a house from 1877, carried out by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
Reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old building and the construction of an entirely new one, but finally he agreed to Gaudí's idea of an unusual and also cheaper renovation.
The Casa Batlló apartment building was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked together with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was precisely on the drawing board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of the reality were made, and his idea was also to use mosaics on the façade.
Numerous other artists and artists also contributed to the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol was involved in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá in Güell Park, which is also home to other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was nicknamed 'bone house' by locals for its organic shapes.
Others called it 'yawning house' because of the special window opening mechanism.
It is also said that at the top of the building there is a picture of the Sword of Saint George, the Patron of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed a central heating system for the house, unique for the time, with ventilation ducts and typical fireplaces.
Their 45 degree inclination seems somewhat bizarre.
In his work Gaudí consistently ignored all building regulations of the time and was not deterred by these at all.
Before construction began, he obtained planning permission from the city, but the information he gave about the planned reconstruction was so vague that when it was completed two years later, the city fathers were so shocked by the result that they demanded remedial action.
Councillors also clashed over the fact that the building, with its piers, even interfered with the public sidewalk.
There was no change, quite the opposite - only fifteen days after the neighbourhood requested it, Josep Batlló applied for permission to let the two highest floors of the house - and was promptly granted it.
The owner of the house himself moved to the lower floors.
The gallery on the second floor had a parlour, while the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment were on the third floor.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story building is lined with stairs leading up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the conversion eliminated all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of the interconnection of rooms.
The social aspect can be fully connected by opening the salon doors, allowing a larger group to chat comfortably, without sacrificing a certain intimacy in more intimate conversations.
The house was renovated by Gaudí and, in addition to a new façade, acquired a rather unusual roof and two additional floors.
Gaudí's play with light is equally impressive, as are the blue and white glazed tiles covering the courtyard and the atriums.
The play of these two colors gives all floors of the house the maximum amount of light.
In doing so, he simply applied the principle that white reflects light better than dark colours, which, on the contrary, absorb sunlight.
The Casa Batlló, inscribed in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, is now open to the public.
On the first floor, the spatial and magnificent apartment is open to the public.
The homeowners decided to take this step only in the year to celebrate the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was determined that this was a fairly profitable business, the tours were retained, and extended to other common rooms as well as the attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
The price for visiting the monument is not a cardboard stick, it is 16,50 Euro. Students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist identification get 20 percent reduction.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees for other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its little dragon turrets, try to make friends with one of the residents of the house and visit him at home.
