This is thought to be related to levels of the male hormone testosterone.
& quot; Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to 60's age, said the co-author of the study, Ros Eeles, Professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should definitely undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if genetic risks or other risk factors are present, such as family health stresses, added Ms. Eeles.
In the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues followed more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer in the UK, as well as 3000 healthy men.
In more than half of the participants in the study, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
These men were equally likely to develop prostate cancer, as were 19 percent of men whose ring and index fingers were the same length.
However, this risk was reduced by 33 percent for men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, and even by 87 percent for men in their 60s.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers, which form already in prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone equals a longer index finger.
Previous research has suggested that testosterone precisely accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, said he was not familiar with the study, but he did not think the relationship between finger length and cancer risk was fully established.
