The Democracy Routine
The pro-democracy movement in Latin America is growing, as is support for private enterprise.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, the influence of Brazil is greater than that of the United States.
These are the results of the Latinobarómetro survey, conducted in 18 countries and exclusively published in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, showing the change of opinion in this region.
There are two facts that caught & apos;'s eye in this year' s survey, conducted in September and October.
Firstly, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In numerous countries along the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has grown sharply (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown at an annual rate of about 6% since 2002, the number of pro-democracy supporters increased from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Mexico, where the economy has rebounded since the sharp slump last year, has also seen a trend.
But only half of those surveyed in Mexico and Brazil, the region's most populous countries, are staunch Democrats, bringing the regional average down (see Chart 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country's democratic practices, up from about 25% last year (Chart 3).
Some 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% their government. Both values correspond to those of last year but show a significant increase since 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America's economic crises undermined efforts to become more democratic.
That this continued during the global economic crisis is perhaps because the countries of Latin America experienced only a short period of recession and quickly recovered.
Moreover, the poor were absorbed by a stronger social safety net.
(According to this week's reports from the United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America, in 2009 the poverty rate in Latin America increased only slightly, and it fell again by 32% this year.)
But there are strong differences in mood from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva are reflected in a widespread sense of progress.
This is less the case in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more pronounced and violent crime has increased.
For only the second time since the survey began, many respondents in Latin America see crime in their country as being more of a problem than unemployment (see Chart 5).
Some 31% say that either they themselves or a family member became the victim of a crime in the last year, but down from 38% last year, the numbers are down to their lowest level since 1995.
The rising economic performance is reflected in the increased support for the private and market economy: approximately 71% of respondents working nationally said that the private sector is essential for development, up from 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Some 58% said that only the market economy can bring progress to their country, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of those surveyed in Venezuela maintained this view (and 80% supported private enterprise), despite the fact that its leftist president, Hugo Chávez, nationalized many private businesses.
Brazil is the most important country in the region, according to 19% of respondents (18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
Respondents in Mexico and most of Central America, on the other hand, consider the US to be the most influential country, with Venezuela taking the role in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
An Election Slap
Nobody expected that the elections on November 28th in Haiti would be perfect.
But the facts far outweighed the fears of the election workers who rushed to the aid of the stricken country.
Crowded ballot boxes, multiple votes cast, ballot boxes in the gutter, destroyed polling stations and intimidation were just some of the problems.
Polling stations were delayed for hours.
Many Haitians, many of whom were made homeless by the earthquake in January, wandered around in search of a place to choose from.
Some eventually gave up completely.
A dozen presidential candidates, including some suspected front-runners, demanded that the election results be annulled because of alleged fraud.
Protests, some of them violent, erupted across the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the head of the UN Mission in Haiti, described the election as fairly good in many respects.
According to a cautious statement by observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community, these irregularities, however serious, do not necessarily invalidate the process.
In other words, the show goes on.
The electoral authority, supposedly beholden to the unpopular outgoing president René Préval and his candidate Jude Célestin, will announce the preliminary results on December 7th.
The expected runoff is scheduled for Jan.
There is still hope in the election.
The two leading opposition candidates, rap musician Michel Martelly and former first lady Mirlande Manigat, have withdrawn their initial invalidity claim.
If Jude Célestin, who has little or no support among voters, is declared the winner of the runoff by the Berhörde, this could create problems.
Due to the cholera epidemic and the fact that more than 1 million of the earthquake's victims are still living in tents, a low turnout was feared.
On Election Day, many Haitians were prevented from voting because of poor organization.
Shortly before the beginning of the vote, approximately 250,000 identification cards needed to vote had not yet been issued.
The stakes are high.
Donor countries see a legitimate, recognized government as an important step in Haiti's reconstruction.
The Haitians themselves agree.
