In the weeks following the sudden death of her husband, Argentina's President, Cristina Fernández, experienced a surge of sympathy, driving her approval rating 20 points higher, to over 50%, the highest since she was elected in 2007.
Whether this helps her win re-election next year depends on whether visibly grieving Cristina Fernández is more willing to compromise than her late husband, her predecessor and political partner Néstor Kirchner.
The characters for this are not unique.
Néstor Kirchner, who steered economic policy even after his wife was elected, often drew up budgets that did not take full account of tax revenues, economic growth, and inflation.
This allowed the presidential couple to spend the extra income as they pleased.
On paper, the Fernández government lost the majority in Congress last year.
