& quot; I will not discuss & quot;, said the President.
The 2010 budget now applies to next year too, giving the President even more scope to spend money as she sees fit.
The economy is running hot: it is likely to grow by up to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently 11.1%, but many private estimates - and union demands - drive it to nearly 30%.
Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina was shaken by economic crises, declared growth and fighting poverty, not reducing inflation, to be his main objectives.
He refused to cooperate with the IMF, bullied the private sector, and cleaned up the National Institute of Statistics and Census, INDEC, which then whittled down the official inflation statistics.
Can Fernández now take a more moderate path?
It has called for talks between the private sector and union leaders.
And officials say they will cap pay increases at 18% next year.
The high world price of Argentina's agricultural products has given a strong boost to the economy.
