The discovery of a foreign species of bacteria that can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new forms of life on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, they believe it is a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously considered essential for life.
& quot; This organism has two possibilities.
& quot; It needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow. & quot;
& quot; This makes it very special, even though it's almost like a & apos; alien & apos; way of life,' explained Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears in the online edition of Science on Thursday.
Six main elements have been considered essential - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
However, as the scientists discovered, the bacterium in California's Mono Lake continues to grow even when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
& quot; One wonders what else is possible & quot; said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
The discovery is an important step in the search for alien life, as scientists need to recognize life and its forms, Anbar said.
The study focuses on microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference, in which no details of the discovery were disclosed, gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could be about the discovery of alien life.
This is not the case.
The discovery & quot; shows that in other planetary systems, organisms can start biochemical processes with the help of other elements, and that the & apos; standard & apos; elements, which we consider absolutely essential for life, are not necessarily pre-determined & quot;, said Charles Cockell, Professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute of the Milton Keynes Open University in the UK.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
& quot; This work is unique because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another, Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the Astrobiological Institute of NASA, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically alike, she assumed that microbes exposed to both could possibly replace one element with the other.
& quot; The toxicity of arsenic is mainly due to the fact that it behaves chemically similar to phosphorus. & quot;
& quot; This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from the other. & quot;
& quot; But the difference is so great that arsenic has a different effect to phosphorus. It enters our biochemical system, where it smears virtually everything, explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing arsenic concentration. It adapted and grew.
While the microbes grow better in phosphorus, the fact that they can also survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon, where arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is nothing new, but there has been no working example yet.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, so science has assumed that early life used it.
& quot; This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently from the early Earth Age & quot;, said Forster, who was not on Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
