Let's face it, Merkel' s position is not a mistake in her publicity.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany is taking on a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, one that conflicts with the maintenance of the traditional traditions of many of its partners.
In view of the opposition in Europe, people in Germany are starting to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the eurozone.
Second: the re-introduction of the Deutschmark - although at this time it sounds more like science fiction - with the support of a large part of the public, about 50% of the population.
The third: reshaping the euro according to German proposals. This means more macroeconomic control; rigorous budgeting; punishing countries that exceed the benchmarks; possibly suspending the payments of some countries, and extending the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been on the cards for some time now. So there are no excuses now.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission provided incentives for deficits, and the German government drafted a constitutional reform to prevent this from happening from 2016 onwards.
This was the first sign of the drift away from what Germany believed was necessary (tight fiscal plans and stable public finances) and from the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second signal came from the central European country, when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to bail out Greece.
That was heavily criticized at the time, but the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public opinion and the public opinion was absolutely against a bailout of Greece.
Finally, Merkel emerges again in the last days of October with a clear position. She demands a reform of the agreements of the European Union, in order to allow the rescue of a country, while obliging private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, because it fuelled the Irish crisis and everything that followed.
But her proposal, albeit somewhat sweetened, was accepted. In the months ahead, we will participate in the reform of the European Union, which should make these measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line, which it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that, even if unpopular measures have to be taken now, the old way of functioning of the euro will cease to exist from this date onwards.
2013 will be the year of a new currency area, in which the offending countries will be severely punished, forced to default, and in this case the private sector will have to bear some of the costs.
Germany shows us that we must pursue a tough course of growth, with high savings and investment rates, consumption moderation, improved productivity and competitiveness, as well as positive external balances.
The other alternative, based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as led by Spain during the boom, is simply unacceptable.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly not to understand it.
It is not just about getting the general government deficit down to three per cent of GDP by 2013.
Demands are much tougher.
And the worst that we could do in these conditions is deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence passes in more serenity.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities offered to us by the spring of 2013.
It appears that Zapatero understood this too, and his dual announcement (the promised reforms after the talks with big business last Saturday and the announcement of new measures yesterday) indicates that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in her own house has taken hold.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it does not look like anything will change.
Among the options being considered, the idea that we would have to leave the euro area stuffed with few serious countries cannot be ruled out.
In that case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sport and rule circumvention
Tricks like those by Alonso and Ramos in the match against Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to avoid a penalty.
The alleged incitement of two Real Madrid players, Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos, in the match on 23 November against Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being shed on whether or not this was an unsporting act and whether or not both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
It is well known that a few minutes before the end of the game the two players lost time (their team had already won clearly) and made several fouls for the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead the group, the two players will fulfill the prescribed sanction in the next league match against Auxerre, thus entering the next match phase without any cards.
The UEFA disciplinary committee fined the club's coach, José Mourinho, two matches and the players involved different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card in such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules that are adhered to in this sport.
Part of the debate surrounding the depicted case comes down to the fact that a team from the football club Real Madrid (who claim nobility and honour in their anthem and on other occasions punished their players for similar incidents) played the leading role, and to the dramatization by Mourinho, who added one episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocateur technician.
In any case, the debate focuses on whether this behaviour, which is expressly prohibited by the statutes, contravenes the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions constitute rule circumvention. In fact, this conduct conforms to the statutes of sport, but appears to circumvent the meaning of the statutes.
In this case, the damage done to the spirit of sport should be investigated.
The spirit of sport defends the physical integrity of the opponent, an aspect that was not compromised by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to prevent the offending players from taking undue advantage of the opposition team. Again, this did not happen.
The paradox of the action taken by the Real Madrid players is that it does not correspond to what we usually understand as cheating or rule evasion, because the evasion of the rule was not done secretly to avoid a penalty, but rather to be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
Players waited and joyfully accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders took from the deliberate fouls.
It is important to emphasize that the rival was not placed in an unfavorable position or advantages were desired for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue with fewer players.
Nor is it a useful strategy for the next game because the club does not have these players.
The advantage, obviously, is that the players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards, which could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, to a certain extent uncertain, because the team could go out at some point. Additionally, this approach punishes the players and moves them into the second card cycle, where they go out with one card less than in the first cycle.
This means that it is not so clear whether it is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices do not undermine the spirit of sport, including strategic decisions to maximize the benefits of the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent any sanction (this would be a clear case of rule circumvention), they wanted to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision not to evade or escape punishment.
Although the line between ingenuity and the rule environment is blurred, I believe that this case is a clear case of ingenuity.
I have the impression that the controversy arose from two factors: because there were two self-exclusions, and because of the way the rules were transmitted.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
