The United States Changes the Rules for obtaining a Visa
Individuals must present themselves to the visa services before they go to the consulate, reducing the cost of the wait.
Starting January 10, 2011, the procedures for obtaining a visa at the Embassy of the United States and at the consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, most applicants will have to present themselves to the visa application service providers (ASC, the first letters in English) before they can talk to each other in the consulate.
The ASC staff collects the biometric data of the applicant, which is verified by the consulate before the interview is held.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa decreases because there is no longer any need to pay separately for the appointment, the processing of the visa application and the transport service providing the document.
The applicant makes only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including temporary workers' visas) and $390 for dealers and investors.
Those wishing only to renew their visa do not need to go to the consulate for a conversation, they only need to go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and get their fingerprints taken.
Since the biometric data is collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment at the consulate will stay there less than before.
Those who apply for the visa at the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo do do not have to pay the 26 dollar service charge anymore.
More information about the new visa application procedure can be found at: http: / / mexico. usembassy. gov / boletines / sp101201 _ Visas-FAQs. html
