Worldwide lighting renewal plan
The UN proposed yesterday in Cancun a plan to renew lighting in homes, commerce and industry in 100 countries to achieve a reduction in greenhouse gases (CFCs), which is almost one-third of the additional reduction that is required to stabilize the earth's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its place in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun, to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments by developed countries.
Under the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem, in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFCs emitted into the earth from lighting, would be avoided if the incandescent white bulbs, which are still a monopoly of 50-70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent LEDs (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of world emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases in the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitters of greenhouse gases, including the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans aimed at reducing global CFC emissions from 53Gt to 49Gt.
However, we would have to subtract another 5 Gt from this balance in order to stabilise the climate increase of 2 degrees Celsius from now to 2020, in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the incandescent white bulbs, 95% of the energy is released in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% is used to produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced by 75%; with the new LED bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced by a factor of two.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last on average between 6000 and 10.000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, such as the one launched this week by the manufacturer Philips - this company, incidentally, participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25.000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-hot bulb, giving an indication of the savings potential of the replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that these completely new light bulbs only emit very little heat, they can also work with a control resistor.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have pointed out that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury, and that they must therefore be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in the developing countries, unless the producers provide a collection point.
However, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent light bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plant, which emits much more mercury to generate the electricity generated by the incandescent light bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power stations emit 25.000 tonnes of mercury per annum.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would generate thanks to this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion annually purchasing electricity and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power stations, which would cost Indonesia $2.5 billion to build.
