Vengeful Hackers and Diligent Spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a dual meaning.
On one hand, it has turned out to be an obvious scandal, a scandal that is merely a scandal in the sense of hypocrisy that governs relations between the states, the citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at an international level, and gives a foretaste of the future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in turn.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by an intelligence service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of newspaper clippings.
The & quot; extraordinary & quot; American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits throw off nothing more than what was published in any magazine for months anyway (except the one Berlusconi owns), and Gadhafi' s horrifyingly caricatured profile has long been the stuff of cabaret artists' sketches.
The rule that the secret files can only consist of news that has already been known is essential to the dynamics of the intelligence services, and not only in this century.
When you go to a library dedicated to Esoteric publications, you will see that each work (The Grail, The Mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, The Templars, or The Rosary) repeats exactly what has been written in previous works.
This is not simply because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (nor because he does not know where to find news about the non-existent), but because those who are dedicated to occult believe in nothing but what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also Dan Brown's success mechanism.
Likewise the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited in spirit) is also the chief of the secret service (otherwise he might be some other guy, like an editor at Libération), who only considers what he acknowledges to be true.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi sent by the American Embassy in Rome to the State Department was the same as the information Newsweek had published the week before.
So why has there been such a fuss about the revelations of these dossiers?
On one page, they state what every educated person already knows: that the embassies - at least since the end of World War II, and since then also when the heads of government can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small tasks of representation, have turned into spy centers.
Any investigative viewer knows this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy to pretend to ignore it.
Nevertheless, the fact that it is repeated in public violates the mission of hypocrisy and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Second, the idea that an x-factor hacker can tap into the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
What is more, the scandal brings about distress not so much for the victims but for the & quot; executioners.
But let's focus on the profound nature of what has happened.
In the days of Orwell, all power could be concentrated like Big Brother, controlling every gesture made by his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy could have proved perfectly correct, since then, when you could control every movement, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway chosen, and so on; the citizen would become the total victim of the eye of power.
If, however, one considers what is happening today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, the control process ceases to be one-sided and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - chosen as the avenger of the citizen - can discover the secrets of power.
How can a power hold out when it is no longer able to keep its own secrets?
True, Georg Simmel has already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is basically a secret free from secrets, because it exposes the public sphere; but to reveal, in the style of WikiLeaks, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets is to deprive her of any power.
WikiLeaks has not wronged Sarkozy or Merkel, but Clinton and Obama did.
What will be the consequences of this insult done to such a tremendous power?
It is obvious that in the future States will not put any kind of reserved information online - that would be like putting a notice board on a street corner.
But it is equally obvious that with the current technologies it is futile to hope to be able to keep confidential reports over telephone.
Nothing is easier than figuring out if and when a Head of State travels on a plane and contacts one of his colleagues.
How could private and only for certain ears be maintained in the future?
I know very well that my prediction at the moment sounds like science fiction and romanticism, but I feel compelled to imagine the government agents, secretly moving assiduously along uncontrollable paths, carrying their communications nowhere else but in my memory, and moreover, hiding the little written information they received in their shoe sale.
The information would be stored in a single copy in locked drawers: basically, the espionage attempt of Watergate had less success than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is advancing like a cancer, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communication, the Internet reconstructs a telegraph with (telephone) wire.
The (analog) videotape enabled film researchers to explore a film tape-by-tape, allowing one to rewind from back to back and unravel all the secrets of the montage, while nowadays (numerical) CDs allow nothing more than to jump from chapter to chapter, that is, in macro portions.
The high-speed train takes three hours to get from Rome to Milan, while it takes three and a half hours to get there by plane, including a transfer.
It is therefore not unusual for politics and communication technology to revert to cars and horses.
One last observation.
In former times, the press tried to understand what secrets were forged between the embassies.
