One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to examine the fulfilment of rapidly dissolved financing promises (also called & quot; Fast Start & quot; or early financing) realized by developing countries.
And here are the rough French rhapsodies.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developing countries committed themselves to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU promised 7.2 billion euros over three years, France 1.26 billion euros (i.e. 420 million euros per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU pulled out all the stops to convince its partners of the fact of their commitment to fast-start financing: a detailed report of actions taken by their Member States, press conferences, major side events, the distribution of brochures.
Operation Transparency is remarkable and highly prized for its real value: the developing countries and civil society would like to see all the developed countries doing the same at the same precision level.
The EU announces that it has released EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to pay respect to its commitment of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if you look into the details, things are a bit more complicated.
This money should, according to the Copenhagen Treaty, be new and additional, in order to ensure that an additional commitment is made without affecting ODA.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus about what & quot; means new and additionally what & quot; means.
While the European Commission proposed harmonization, certain member states, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone selects the benchmark they consider to be the best.
The European Commission has chosen, for example, the benchmark for 2009: international financing will be retained and 150 million will be added over three years under the & quot; Fast-Start & quot; financing scheme.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or in terms of ODA.
In return, France considered that the financing of all new projects & quot; of 2010 was new and additionally quot;.
In other words, there are no benchmark levels of spending for the preceding year, or for ODA at global level.
Specifically, the total amount of French support to developing countries may remain stable (or decrease) - France claims to be honouring its commitment to provide new and additional funding.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule on this yet, and everyone chooses his calculation mode.
Some, such as France, have 1 borrowed €as the equivalent of 1 donated €.
Obviously, it is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If loans for specific profitable investments (often carbon-mitigation projects based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceitful to present the Euro collected as the equivalent of a donated Euro... Moreover, only the cost of the loan for the donor country should be counted as the commitment (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing else in mind but the following consideration: respecting & quot; its commitment of 420 million by borrowing 91.5% (389.8 million euros and donating 8.5%) 36.1 million euros - see also the EU document to see for yourself.
France is the only EU country to use loans on a large scale.
Germany charges 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) pay 100% of their obligations through donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to meet its obligations, France gives just 10 cents, which is a comparable amount of money.
Beautiful hocus-pocus!
Overall, France is operating with a double fraud in its Fast-Start financing: on the one hand, the action is evolving over time, and on the other hand, the reality of the financial commitment.
France succeeds in giving the impression that it has spent 420 million euros of new and additional money in accordance with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
Manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (since it seems that it was Bercy who did the arbitrage) could have a doubly negative effect; once intra-EU (why do the other member states continue to donate, if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, because the developing countries are not completely deceived...
The chapter of premature financing only a small question in relatively short time compared to the totality of discussions about the climate.
But it might be one drop too many in the UNFCCC's immense machinery.
Let's hope that does not happen.
Be that as it may, it is imperative to learn the lessons of this first year of premature financing.
First and foremost, France could announce a change in its accounting method for the years 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respect for its obligations and of compensatory justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, France could move forward with discussions on the subject of long-term financing (another crucial and currently debated topic): it cannot escape the question of & quot; accountability or the accounting nature of its loans.
France might change its position to be as progressive on the issues as it is on other things.
The hope is therefore based on the new Environment Minister, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, arriving in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's Fast-Start and its vision of & quot; accountability and loan usage would by its very nature raise the international confidence base necessary for further discussion.
Alarm - Pesticides ingested by children
A child of 10 years of age consumes 81 different chemical substances over the course of the day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Association Génération Futures (Former Movement for the Protection of the Rights and the Respect of Future Generations).
The association, which declares that the & quot; results do n 't reflect a statistically significant value because of the small number of samples analysed, but rather represent the illustrative character of the problem discussed. & quot; purchased the food usually consumed with meals by a child of about ten, plus a snack, from supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September.
These typical meals - including the official recommendations of five pieces of fresh fruit and fruit, three dairy products, and 1.5 liters of water a day - were studied, as well as nibbles from laboratories in search of chemical substances, pesticides, heavy metals, and other pollutants.
The balance of plates is staggering: 81 chemical substances, 42 of which are classified as possibly or probably carcinogenic, 5 classified as safe carcinogenic, as well as 37 substances with endocrine disrupting factor, according to studies of several institutions, such as the International Cancer Research Center.
& quot; Even if in approximately the entirety of cases the legal limits are not exceeded for each chemical, individually consumed substance, it is well inferred from this survey that the reality in which the consumer is potentially exposed to carcinogenic substances or substances with endocrinine disturbing factor is worrying.
Already at breakfast, the butter and tea with milk alone contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues, three of the safely proven carcinogenic residues, as well as more than twenty residues which can affect the hormonal system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended for use as a snack in the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide which is banned in France.
The same applies to green beans from Kenya, included in lunch, where the study found traces of an insecticide strictly prohibited in the EU.
There were also minced meat, tuna from the can, even baguette and chewing gum laced with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak was the most & quot; abundant with 34 chemical residues detected, and even the plastic plate used to warm the meal in the microwave was not uncontaminated.
The ultimate risk of this' quot; pollutant cocktail 'for the consumer' quot; is likely to be underestimated ', the study states.
The & quot; Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts & quot; (EE-LV;) proposed, in view of the urgency of the situation, to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides in order to halt the & quot; increase in diseases affecting civilization.
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) on the presence of residues identified 365 different pesticides found in fruit and vegetables that are consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
